    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n    <meta charset=\"UTF-8\">\n    <meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0\">\n    <title>Type System Demonstration</title>\n    <style>\n        body {\n            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n            line-height: 1.6;\n            max-width: 800px;\n            margin: 0 auto;\n            padding: 20px;\n            color: #333;\n        }\n        h1 {\n            color: #2c3e50;\n            border-bottom: 2px solid #3498db;\n            padding-bottom: 10px;\n        }\n        .example {\n            background-color: #f9f9f9;\n            border-left: 4px solid #3498db;\n            padding: 15px;\n            margin: 20px 0;\n            border-radius: 0 5px 5px 0;\n        }\n        .output {\n            background-color: #e8f4f8;\n            padding: 10px;\n            margin-top: 10px;\n            border-radius: 5px;\n            white-space: pre-wrap;\n        }\n        button {\n            background-color: #3498db;\n            color: white;\n            border: none;\n            padding: 8px 15px;\n            border-radius: 4px;\n            cursor: pointer;\n            margin: 5px 0;\n        }\n        button:hover {\n            background-color: #2980b9;\n        }\n        .type-info {\n            font-weight: bold;\n            color: #e74c3c;\n        }\n    </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n    <h1>Type System in JavaScript</h1>\n    <p>JavaScript has a dynamic type system where types are associated with values, not variables. This is different from statically typed languages where types are associated with variables.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"example\">\n        <h2>1. Primitive Types</h2>\n        <p>JavaScript has 7 primitive data types:</p>\n        <ul>\n            <li>string</li>\n            <li>number</li>\n            <li>bigint</li>\n            <li>boolean</li>\n            <li>symbol</li>\n            <li>null</li>\n            <li>undefined</li>\n        </ul>\n        <button onclick=\"showPrimitiveTypes()\">Show Primitive Types</button>\n        <div id=\"primitiveOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"example\">\n        <h2>2. Dynamic Typing</h2>\n        <p>The same variable can hold values of different types:</p>\n        <button onclick=\"showDynamicTyping()\">Show Dynamic Typing</button>\n        <div id=\"dynamicOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"example\">\n        <h2>3. Type Coercion</h2>\n        <p>JavaScript automatically converts types in certain contexts:</p>\n        <button onclick=\"showTypeCoercion()\">Show Type Coercion</button>\n        <div id=\"coercionOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"example\">\n        <h2>4. Type Checking</h2>\n        <p>You can check types using <code>typeof</code> operator:</p>\n        <button onclick=\"showTypeChecking()\">Show Type Checking</button>\n        <div id=\"checkingOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <div class=\"example\">\n        <h2>5. Objects and Arrays</h2>\n        <p>Non-primitive types (objects, arrays, functions) are all considered objects:</p>\n        <button onclick=\"showObjectTypes()\">Show Object Types</button>\n        <div id=\"objectOutput\" class=\"output\"></div>\n    </div>\n\n    <script>\n        function showPrimitiveTypes() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('primitiveOutput');\n            let result = '';\n            \n            // String\n            const str = \"Hello\";\n            result += `\"${str}\" is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof str}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // Number\n            const num = 42;\n            result += `${num} is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof num}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // BigInt\n            const big = 123n;\n            result += `${big} is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof big}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // Boolean\n            const bool = true;\n            result += `${bool} is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof bool}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // Symbol\n            const sym = Symbol('unique');\n            result += `${sym.toString()} is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof sym}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // Null (quirky in JS)\n            const nul = null;\n            result += `null is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof nul}</span> (historical bug)\\n`;\n            \n            // Undefined\n            let undef;\n            result += `undefined is of type: <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof undef}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            output.innerHTML = result;\n        }\n\n        function showDynamicTyping() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('dynamicOutput');\n            let result = '';\n            \n            let dynamicVar = \"I'm a string\";\n            result += `Initially: ${dynamicVar} (${typeof dynamicVar})\\n`;\n            \n            dynamicVar = 42;\n            result += `Now: ${dynamicVar} (${typeof dynamicVar})\\n`;\n            \n            dynamicVar = true;\n            result += `Now: ${dynamicVar} (${typeof dynamicVar})\\n`;\n            \n            dynamicVar = { name: \"Object\" };\n            result += `Now: ${JSON.stringify(dynamicVar)} (${typeof dynamicVar})\\n`;\n            \n            output.innerHTML = result;\n        }\n\n        function showTypeCoercion() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('coercionOutput');\n            let result = '';\n            \n            // String + Number\n            result += `\"5\" + 2 = <span class=\"type-info\">${\"5\" + 2}</span> (string concatenation)\\n`;\n            \n            // Number + String\n            result += `5 + \"2\" = <span class=\"type-info\">${5 + \"2\"}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            // Subtraction triggers number conversion\n            result += `\"5\" - 2 = <span class=\"type-info\">${\"5\" - 2}</span> (numeric operation)\\n`;\n            \n            // Boolean in numeric context\n            result += `true + 1 = <span class=\"type-info\">${true + 1}</span> (true becomes 1)\\n`;\n            result += `false + 1 = <span class=\"type-info\">${false + 1}</span> (false becomes 0)\\n`;\n            \n            // Loose equality comparison\n            result += `5 == \"5\" = <span class=\"type-info\">${5 == \"5\"}</span> (type coercion)\\n`;\n            result += `5 === \"5\" = <span class=\"type-info\">${5 === \"5\"}</span> (strict equality)\\n`;\n            \n            output.innerHTML = result;\n        }\n\n        function showTypeChecking() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('checkingOutput');\n            let result = '';\n            \n            function checkType(value) {\n                return `typeof ${JSON.stringify(value)} = <span class=\"type-info\">${typeof value}</span>`;\n            }\n            \n            result += checkType(\"hello\") + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(42) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(true) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(null) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(undefined) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType({}) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType([]) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(() => {}) + \"\\n\";\n            result += checkType(Symbol()) + \"\\n\";\n            \n            // Special case for arrays\n            const arr = [1, 2, 3];\n            result += `\\nArray.isArray(${JSON.stringify(arr)}) = <span class=\"type-info\">${Array.isArray(arr)}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            output.innerHTML = result;\n        }\n\n        function showObjectTypes() {\n            const output = document.getElementById('objectOutput');\n            let result = '';\n            \n            const obj = { name: \"John\", age: 30 };\n            result += `Plain object: ${JSON.stringify(obj)} (${typeof obj})\\n`;\n            \n            const arr = [1, 2, 3];\n            result += `Array: ${JSON.stringify(arr)} (${typeof arr}) - isArray? ${Array.isArray(arr)}\\n`;\n            \n            function greet() { return \"Hello\"; }\n            result += `Function: ${greet.toString()} (${typeof greet})\\n`;\n            \n            const date = new Date();\n            result += `Date: ${date} (${typeof date})\\n`;\n            \n            // All non-primitives are objects\n            result += `\\nIs array instance of Object? <span class=\"type-info\">${arr instanceof Object}</span>\\n`;\n            result += `Is function instance of Object? <span class=\"type-info\">${greet instanceof Object}</span>\\n`;\n            result += `Is date instance of Object? <span class=\"type-info\">${date instanceof Object}</span>\\n`;\n            \n            output.innerHTML = result;\n        }\n    </script>\n</body>\n</html>"
